# This should point to the small dataset of the Kaggle Dogs vs Cats competition that was created in a previous notebook
data_folder = pathlib.Path('../datasets/kaggle_dogs_vs_cats_small')

train_dataset = image_dataset_from_directory(
    data_folder / "train",
    image_size=(180, 180),
    batch_size=16)
validation_dataset = image_dataset_from_directory(
    data_folder / "validation",
    image_size=(180, 180),
    batch_size=16)
test_dataset = image_dataset_from_directory(
    data_folder / "test",
    image_size=(180, 180),
    batch_size=16)

# Get class names and counts for every class
class_names = train_dataset.class_names
train_counts = np.concatenate([y for x, y in train_dataset], axis=0)
val_counts = np.concatenate([y for x, y in validation_dataset], axis=0)
test_counts = np.concatenate([y for x, y in test_dataset], axis=0)

train_class_counts = [sum(train_counts == i) for i in range(len(class_names))]
val_class_counts = [sum(val_counts == i) for i in range(len(class_names))]
test_class_counts = [sum(test_counts == i) for i in range(len(class_names))]

# Plot class distribution
fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 3, figsize=(15, 5))
ax[0].bar(class_names, train_class_counts)
ax[0].set_title('Training Set')
ax[1].bar(class_names, val_class_counts)
ax[1].set_title('Validation Set')
ax[2].bar(class_names, test_class_counts)
ax[2].set_title('Test Set')
plt.suptitle('Class Distribution Across Datasets')
plt.show()

It can be noticed that across all sets the classes are well-balanced.

Models' training¶

Custom CNN¶

In [52]:
def make_custom_cnn_model(input_shape=(180, 180, 3)):
    inputs = keras.Input(shape=input_shape)
    x = layers.Rescaling(1./255)(inputs)
    x = layers.Conv2D(32, 3, activation="relu")(x)
    x = layers.MaxPooling2D(2)(x)
    x = layers.Conv2D(64, 3, activation="relu")(x)
    x = layers.MaxPooling2D(2)(x)
    x = layers.Conv2D(128, 3, activation="relu")(x)
    x = layers.MaxPooling2D(2)(x)
    x = layers.Flatten()(x)
    x = layers.Dense(256, activation="relu")(x)
    x = layers.Dropout(0.5)(x)
    outputs = layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid")(x)
    return keras.Model(inputs, outputs)

custom_cnn_model = make_custom_cnn_model()

Fine-Tuned VGG16¶

In [54]:
# Load pre-trained VGG16 
conv_base = keras.applications.VGG16(
    weights="imagenet",
    include_top=False,
    input_shape=(180, 180, 3))

# Build new model layers on top
inputs = keras.Input(shape=(180, 180, 3))
x = keras.applications.vgg16.preprocess_input(inputs)
x = conv_base(x)
x = layers.Flatten()(x)
x = layers.Dense(256, activation="relu")(x)
x = layers.Dropout(0.5)(x)
outputs = layers.Dense(1, activation="sigmoid")(x)
vgg_model = keras.Model(inputs, outputs)

vgg_model.summary()

Evaluating performance¶

In [57]:
# Plot training history (accuracy) for CNN and VGG16 model
plt.figure(figsize=(12, 5))
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.plot(history_custom.history["accuracy"], label="Training Accuracy")
plt.plot(history_custom.history["val_accuracy"], label="Validation Accuracy")
plt.title("Custom CNN Model Accuracy")
plt.legend()

plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
plt.plot(history_vgg.history["accuracy"], label="Training Accuracy")
plt.plot(history_vgg.history["val_accuracy"], label="Validation Accuracy")
plt.title("VGG16 Model Accuracy")
plt.legend()
plt.show()
  • Since the Custom CNN model's training accuracy increases rapidly (nearly reaches 100%) and fluctuates around 65–70% during validation, this may be a sign that the model is overfitting the training data.
  • On the other hand, VGG16 performs significantly better in terms of both training and validation accuracy. It generalizes well and avoids overfitting compared to the custom model.

Regarding loss:

  • A clear gap between training and validation loss after around epoch 5 shows strong overfitting for the Custom CNN model.
  • However, for VGG16 the difference in loss is relatively small, suggesting good generalization.

# Converting predictions into classes

vgg_class_preds = (vgg_preds > 0.5).astype("int32")

# Get true labels
true_labels = np.concatenate([y for x, y in test_dataset], axis=0)

For both models, some of the misclassified examples show that the models may struggle when the clarity of the image is low.

Conclusions¶

  • The custom CNN performs barely better than random guessing (64% test accuracy) while the fine-tuned VGG16 excels in perfomance (97% accuracy).
  • The VGG16 model maintains aproximately 48% over precision, recall, and F1-score across both categories, while the custom model shows a significant better performance on dogs over cats (Higher recall for dogs).
  • The evaluation over test set shows the superiority of transfer learning bu using VGG16 model.
  • Since custom CNN is learning all its weights, it requires substantially more data to build a competitive model.

Overall, I conclude that transfer learning with pre-trained models is overwhelmingly superior for this image classification task, achieving near-human level performance while the custom CNN model fails to learn effective discriminative features.
